  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Record of Lee Mujee's Stewardship of Cheongju
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Cheongju, a prefecture in Yangguang Province, borders Chungju and Gongju. Its lands breed many local strongmen, yet its magistrates uphold the law and its people remain docile. However, those who come to govern waver between leniency and harshness, some merely passing through without care. Thus the clerks and commoners differ little from other regions. Grain quotas feed the public coffers, granaries fill for guests—yet no consistent method governs these things. Some governors press the people cruelly, making them suffer, making officials corrupt. These abuses have festered long. Though rare individuals achieve balance between strictness and mercy, restoring what was lost and forgotten, their works die with them. Rarely does one establish lasting law that stitches together the state and people, that removes old corruption and brings peace to both officials and commoners.

    Lee Mujee of Yonggu was my fellow student at the National Academy. Our peers praised his learning. When the council took notice and elevated him to minor official, recent custom forbade such officials from examination. Yet he stands unblemished beside those who passed the tests. Observing his governance reveals his wisdom.

    The rare achievement I spoke of—surely it is his. Cheongju had been ravaged by pirates, its streets emptied and villages broken. When Mujee was appointed its governor, he inquired, planned, and nurtured the people with warmth. Within two years, prosperity returned, the people felt kinship, officials honored law. His good governance reached the capital's ears. Though duty called him elsewhere, the court would not replace him—so attached were they to his service of the people. Though Mujee suffered long in remote posts, the court's love for its people shone clear.

    From his frugality, Mujee gathered: twenty sacks of white rice, seventy of barley, eighty of millet, thirty of buckwheat, a thousand bolts of cloth. Cloth and grain, once spent, are gone. Better to establish a fund that yields interest and endures. Yet he reflected: "After I depart, if each successor holds my heart, the principal remains. But if not, whence comes the interest? In years my method dissolves, alas! Moreover, words fade and writings scatter. Without worthy keepers, the world dismisses them. But let a master of letters record these deeds—then they spread far. Though Cheongju burn my tablets, they cannot erase them. When future governors come and ask, 'The record says this—where now are the rice and cloth?' the destroyer stands speechless."

    Thus he wrote to Han Sanjaek seeking this record. His brother, Counselor Park, came to my house urging its completion. I hold the post of Keeper of Records. When I hear of goodness, I must write it. Therefore I write this record.
  footnotes:
    - Lee Mujee (李慕之), also known as Yonggu (龍駒), was a student and colleague of the author at the National Academy (Sungkyunkwan). His refusal to take the civil service examination despite his qualifications reflects the rigid bureaucratic restrictions of the era.
    - The 'pirate raids' (倭寇) refer to Japanese pirate incursions that devastated Korean coastal and inland regions during the Goryeo-Joseon transition period.
    - The author, Lee Saek (1328-1396), here identifies himself by his title as Keeper of Records (太史) and his pen name Han Sanjaek (韓山子), reflecting his dual roles as official historian and scholar.
    - Mujee's frugal accumulation of grain and cloth represents a revolutionary administrative innovation—the establishment of a sustainable public fund with revolving interest, designed to outlast any individual governor's tenure.
    - The metaphor of burning the wooden tablets yet unable to erase the written record reflects the power of literature to preserve virtue beyond physical destruction, a central concern of Confucian historiography.
